    "created_at": "2025-11-18T08:51:46Z",
    "updated_at": "2025-11-18T08:52:58Z",
    "body": "> I would say it is unlikely that excluding processes by name well be implemented in the near future. It may be possible for you to change the module format string to `'([$symbol$number]($style) )'`. Since other shells usually don't hit this bug, perhaps nushell can optimise the timing auf launching background jobs for cases like this.\n\nI think it's a conceptual issue of starship, not of nushell. It's probably not occuring or rarely occuring in other shells because of the speed of nushell. Having some task running in the background after a line of code is run isn't that unusual, but you won't want everything to show up in the indicator.\nRaising the threshold would just eliminate the usage of the module in this scenario. Lets assume I run neovim and pause it with ctrl + z. There would be one background task that I would expect to be displayed by the module, but if I just press enter without adding any input to the current line, it wouldn't show up. Then when I add input it would show 2.\nHaving an exclusion filter is probably the simplest solution here, expect you have any better idea for filtering out something from the module.",
    "author_association": "NONE",
